{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d06d53cb-6626-47dc-8749-6bc60b6b2ad7","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` only tells the page layout not to inset for safe areas — but on **Android** the window still doesn't draw behind the system bars by default. You need to explicitly enable edge-to-edge mode.\n\n**What to add on Android** — in your `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Activity;\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    EdgeToEdge.Enable(this);\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);\n}\n```\n\n**On iOS**, make sure you also have the platform-specific property:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;\n             assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**Common additional gotchas:**\n\n1. If using **Shell**, hide the navigation chrome:\n   ```xml\n   Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n   Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n   ```\n\n2. Make sure your `Image` fills the page:\n   ```xml\n   <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n          Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n          HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n          VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n   ```\n\nThe combination of Android edge-to-edge + iOS `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` + `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should give you the true full-bleed layout.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98f584d7-6b19-4039-be22-dc76d6eac9f3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is building a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge (behind status bar and navigation bar). They've set `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common issue in .NET MAUI. Let me think about what they might be missing:\n\n1. In .NET MAUI, `IgnoreSafeArea` is a property on views, and there's also page-level safe area handling.\n\n2. For .NET 10 (which would be the latest), there have been changes to how safe areas work. Let me think about what's needed:\n   - On Android, edge-to-edge display requires explicit opt-in, especially for versions before Android 15 where it's now the default.\n   - On iOS, safe areas need to be handled at the page level since the platform has specific requirements around status and navigation bars.\n   - The `IgnoreSafeArea` property works on individual views, but I need to check if there's a page-level setting that overrides the safe area behavior entirely.\n\nLet me reconsider the actual APIs available. The platform-specific approach on iOS uses `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` to disable safe area constraints, while Android requires enabling edge-to-edge mode. I'm not certain about `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` being a standard property—that might be from a different framework or a custom implementation. I should focus on what I know works in current .NET MAUI versions and clarify the distinction between page-level and view-level safe area handling. to ignore safe areas is:\n- For iOS: `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` \n- For individual views: setting `IgnoreSafeArea` \n\nBut even with safe area disabled, on Android you still need to handle the system bars (status bar and navigation bar). The app content doesn't go behind them by default unless you enable edge-to-edge mode.\n\nFor Android edge-to-edge in .NET MAUI, you typically need to:\n1. Set the window to draw behind system bars using `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` or the newer Android API\n2. Make the status bar and navigation bar transparent\n\nIn .NET MAUI for Android, this is often done in `MainActivity.cs` or by using platform-specific code.\n\nFor .NET 10 MAUI specifically, there might be built-in support for edge-to-edge. The user is likely missing the Android edge-to-edge configuration since `SafeAreaEdges` alone won't make content extend behind system bars. On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` or `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` should work, though they might also need to ensure the image's `Aspect` is set to `AspectFill` and the layout isn't constraining it.\n\nSo the answer is: they need platform-specific setup on Android to enable edge-to-edge rendering, not just safe area configuration.","outputTokens":1645,"requestId":"483D:B22B0:BEC20B:DDA01C:69F3FDC8"},"id":"d2b564e1-9526-43a2-ae69-608524d380b5","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:12:07.707Z","parentId":"038979bf-9da4-474a-8b39-5714aaa8fa0c"}
